4. Analytical Results: Theorem‑Driven Roadmap

4.1 Well‑Posedness and Forward Invariance (Theorem 1)

Theorem 1 (Forward Invariance). For any initial condition X(0) \in \mathcal{M}^N, the system has a unique solution for all t \ge 0, and \mathcal{M}^N is forward invariant.

Proof. The vector field F is polynomial, hence locally Lipschitz. By Picard–Lindelöf, a unique local solution exists. To prove forward invariance, we verify the Bouligand tangent cone condition (Nagumo’s theorem). For the closed convex set \mathcal{M}^N = \prod_{i,k} [0,1], the tangent cone at a boundary point is characterized by the sign of the derivative on each face.

· Lower face x_i^k = 0: The vector field component is
  \dot{x}_i^k = \sigma\sum_{j\neq k}\tilde{S}_{jk}x_i^j + \beta\sum_\ell A_{i\ell}x_\ell^k \ge 0,
  because all terms are non‑negative. Hence the field points into \mathcal{M}^N or is tangent.
· Upper face x_i^k = 1: Using x_i^j(1-x_i^k)=0 and 1-x_i^k/K_k = 1-1/K_k, we have
  \dot{x}_i^k = r_k\left(1 - \frac{1}{K_k}\right) - \mu_k.
  Since K_k \le 1, we have 1-1/K_k \le 0. Thus \dot{x}_i^k \le -\mu_k \le 0. If \mu_k>0, the field is strictly inward; if \mu_k=0 and K_k=1, the face is invariant.

Because the field lies in the tangent cone at every boundary point, Nagumo’s theorem guarantees that \mathcal{M}^N is forward invariant. Global existence follows from boundedness of the solution. ∎

