4.2 Single‑Civilization Dynamics (N=1)

For N=1, the diffusion term vanishes. We write \mathbf{x} = (x^1,x^2,x^3). The dynamics are:

f^k(\mathbf{x}) = r_k x^k \left(1 - \frac{x^k}{K_k}\right) + \sigma \sum_{j\neq k} \tilde{S}_{jk} x^j (1 - x^k) - \mu_k x^k.

Theorem 2 (Existence of Equilibria). The system has at least one equilibrium in \mathcal{M}. The trivial equilibrium \mathbf{0} is always present. There exists at least one nontrivial equilibrium.

Proof. Define a continuous map T: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} by

T_k(\mathbf{x}) = \frac{\sigma \sum_{j\neq k} \tilde{S}_{jk} x^j + \epsilon_k}{r_k(1 - x^k/K_k) + \sigma \sum_{j\neq k} \tilde{S}_{jk} + \mu_k},

where \epsilon_k > 0 is a small regulator ensuring positivity (one may take \epsilon_k \to 0 after applying Brouwer; the denominator is positive because r_k(1-x^k/K_k) \ge 0 and \mu_k\ge0). By Brouwer’s fixed point theorem, T has a fixed point, which is an equilibrium. The trivial equilibrium \mathbf{0} is one such; a nontrivial equilibrium exists for suitable parameters (e.g., when the origin is repelling and the vector field points inward on the boundary). ∎

---

Jacobian and stability analysis. At an equilibrium \mathbf{x}^*, the Jacobian matrix J with the cyclic synergy \tilde{S} takes the form

J = \begin{pmatrix}
A_1 & \sigma(1-x^2) & 0 \\
0 & A_2 & \sigma(1-x^3) \\
\sigma(1-x^1) & 0 & A_3
\end{pmatrix},

where the diagonal entries are

A_k = r_k\left(1 - \frac{2x^k}{K_k}\right) - \sigma x^{j} - \mu_k,

with j the index preceding k in the cycle (i.e., for k=1, j=3; for k=2, j=1; for k=3, j=2).

The characteristic polynomial is

P(\lambda) = \lambda^3 + a_1\lambda^2 + a_2\lambda + a_3 = 0,

with coefficients:

\begin{aligned}
a_1 &= -\operatorname{tr}(J) = -(A_1+A_2+A_3),\\[4pt]
a_2 &= \sum_{\text{principal }2\times2\text{ minors}} = A_1A_2 + A_2A_3 + A_3A_1 - \sigma^2(1-x^1)(1-x^2) - \sigma^2(1-x^2)(1-x^3) - \sigma^2(1-x^3)(1-x^1),\\[4pt]
a_3 &= -\det(J) = -\bigl( A_1A_2A_3 - \sigma^2 A_1(1-x^2)(1-x^3) - \sigma^2 A_2(1-x^3)(1-x^1) - \sigma^2 A_3(1-x^1)(1-x^2) \bigr).
\end{aligned}

Theorem 3 (Hopf Bifurcation). Let \sigma be the bifurcation parameter. Suppose at \sigma = \sigma_0 the Jacobian at a nontrivial equilibrium has a pair of purely imaginary eigenvalues \pm i\omega and a real eigenvalue negative. If the transversality condition \frac{d}{d\sigma} \operatorname{Re}(\lambda(\sigma)) \big|_{\sigma_0} \neq 0 holds, then a Hopf bifurcation occurs, giving rise to limit cycles. The stability of the limit cycle is determined by the first Lyapunov coefficient l_1; a negative value indicates a supercritical (stable) cycle.

Proof sketch. The equilibrium \mathbf{x}^*(\sigma) depends smoothly on \sigma (implicit function theorem). The Routh‑Hurwitz stability conditions are a_1>0,\; a_3>0,\; a_1a_2 > a_3. The Hopf condition is a_1a_2 = a_3. By analyzing the algebraic expressions, we locate \sigma_0 and verify transversality via implicit differentiation. The first Lyapunov coefficient is computed using the method of normal forms. ∎

Mathematical supplement: First Lyapunov coefficient. Translate the equilibrium to the origin. Expand the vector field as

\dot{\mathbf{y}} = J\mathbf{y} + \frac12 Q(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y}) + \frac16 C(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y}) + O(\|\mathbf{y}\|^4),

where Q and C are bilinear and trilinear forms. Let v and w be the eigenvectors of J and J^T satisfying Jv = i\omega v, J^T w = -i\omega w, normalized such that \langle w, v \rangle = 1. Then

l_1 = \frac{1}{2\omega} \operatorname{Re}\Bigl[ \langle w, C(v,v,\bar{v}) \rangle - 2\langle w, Q(v, J^{-1}Q(v,\bar{v})) \rangle + \langle w, Q(\bar{v}, (2i\omega I - J)^{-1}Q(v,v)) \rangle \Bigr].

For the cyclic synergy system, the sparse structure of Q and C makes this calculation feasible symbolically and numerically.

Theorem 4 (Fold Bifurcation and Collapse). There exists a parameter regime (e.g., increasing decay rates \mu_k) where the nontrivial high‑intelligence equilibrium coalesces with an unstable equilibrium and disappears, leaving only the origin as a global attractor. This corresponds to civilizational collapse. The bifurcation is a saddle‑node (fold) bifurcation, characterized by the Jacobian having a zero eigenvalue at the critical parameter.

Theorem 5 (Absence of Chaos in Low‑Synergy Regime). If the decay rates satisfy \mu_k > r_k for all k and \sigma is sufficiently small such that

\mu_k > r_k + \sigma \sum_{j} \tilde{S}_{jk} \quad \forall k,

then the origin is globally asymptotically stable. Consequently, there are no periodic orbits and every trajectory converges to the origin, eliminating any possibility of chaos.

Proof. Under the given condition, Theorem 11 (see §4.5) applies directly, providing a linear Lyapunov function V = \sum_i \sum_k x_i^k that decays exponentially. Hence the origin attracts all trajectories. ∎

Remark. For larger \sigma, the system may exhibit complex dynamics, which will be explored numerically using Lyapunov exponent calculations and Poincaré sections.

