4.3 Networked Civilizations on Regular Graphs

Now consider N identical civilizations coupled via logistic diffusion on a d-regular undirected graph (so that A\mathbf{1} = d\mathbf{1}). Let L = dI - A be the graph Laplacian, with eigenvalues 0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \cdots \le \lambda_N.

Theorem 6 (Stability of Homogeneous Equilibria via Master Stability Function). Let \mathbf{x}^* be a homogeneous equilibrium (all civilizations identical). Linearize around \mathbf{x}^*. Because the graph is regular, the Laplacian eigenvectors diagonalize the linearization. For each Laplacian eigenvalue \lambda_\ell, the linearized dynamics in the corresponding mode are governed by the matrix

J_{\text{int}} - \beta(1 - x^{*k}) \lambda_\ell I,

where J_{\text{int}} is the 3\times 3 Jacobian of the single‑civilization dynamics at \mathbf{x}^*. Define the master stability function \psi(\sigma) as the maximum real part of the eigenvalues of J_{\text{int}} - \sigma I. The homogeneous equilibrium is stable if \psi(\beta(1 - x^{*k}) \lambda_\ell) < 0 for all \ell.

Proof. The diffusion term linearizes to -\beta(1-x^{*k}) L \xi_i^k for each capacity k. Because the graph is regular, L and the identity commute, so the eigenvectors of L block‑diagonalize the full 3N \times 3N Jacobian. The result follows. ∎

Theorem 7 (Turing Instability). For a range of parameters (e.g., when J_{\text{int}} has a structure analogous to an activator–inhibitor system), the homogeneous equilibrium can become unstable when \beta exceeds a critical value \beta_c. This diffusion‑induced instability leads to spatial patterning: civilizations spontaneously differentiate into “intelligent hubs” and “peripheral” societies. The critical \beta_c satisfies \psi(\beta_c(1 - x^{*k}) \lambda_2) = 0, where \lambda_2 is the algebraic connectivity (Fiedler value).

Theorem 8 (Synchronization). When \beta is sufficiently large, all civilizations converge to the same trajectory (complete synchronization). The condition for synchronization is that the maximum transverse Lyapunov exponent (given by the master stability function for \lambda_\ell > 0) is negative.

