5. Computational Architecture (Supplementary Material)

To numerically verify the analytical results and provide a tool for future researchers, we will develop a Python library civ_intel with the following modules:

· dynamics.py: Implements the vector field \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}) using the reduced synergy matrix S = \sigma \tilde{S}. Functions for computing the Jacobian and for numerical integration. Symbolic tools (SymPy) will be used to generate the Routh‑Hurwitz coefficients and to detect Hopf bifurcations via root‑finding on a_1a_2 - a_3.
· network.py: Uses NetworkX to generate d-regular graphs (e.g., random regular graphs, circulant graphs). Computes the Laplacian spectrum.
· solver.py: Wrapper for scipy.integrate.solve_ivp with event detection for root‑finding. Includes a continuation tool to trace equilibria as parameters vary.
· bifurcation.py: Implements a simple numerical bifurcation detector (e.g., by tracking eigenvalues and detecting sign changes in the Routh‑Hurwitz conditions). For validated continuation, we will interface with pycont or use MATLAB’s MatCont via a bridge.
· msf.py: Computes the master stability function for a given Jacobian and Laplacian spectrum.
· stochastic.py: Implements the density‑dependent Markov process (Gillespie algorithm) to verify the Fokker‑Planck approximation.
· examples/: Jupyter notebooks reproducing the theorems (e.g., Hopf bifurcation in N=1, Turing patterns on a ring graph, mean‑field simulation, ISS under noise).

All code will be open‑source, documented, and archived on GitHub. It serves as a verification of the analytical proofs and as a foundation for future empirical parameterization.

